00:12.000 --> 00:15.000
Because goals are the first thing we define

00:15.000 --> 00:23.000
I would like to focus on the goals of the merchandiser and the salesperson

00:23.000 --> 00:27.000
I would like to draw your attention to the fact that these are different goals

00:27.000 --> 00:35.000
And you should consider the goals of the salesperson when you come to her and offer your standard

00:35.000 --> 00:38.000
You should understand what they want

00:38.000 --> 00:41.000
Let's look at the goals of the manufacturer

00:41.000 --> 00:46.000
Increasing the turnover and volume of sales of your own product

00:46.000 --> 00:54.000
If you pay attention to the salesperson's goals, you will see that the salesperson's turnover is increasing

00:54.000 --> 00:58.000
It doesn't matter if your product is increasing or someone else's

00:58.000 --> 01:01.000
The main thing is that the turnover of the store becomes larger

01:01.000 --> 01:08.000
The next goal of the manufacturer is to draw attention to its own assortment, to its own trademark

01:08.000 --> 01:13.000
And this is understandable because our goal is to promote our trademark to the market

01:13.000 --> 01:16.000
And what does the salesperson tell us?

01:16.000 --> 01:21.000
The salesperson says that it is important for him to optimize the assortment of the store as a whole

01:21.000 --> 01:25.000
Because the store provides a service for selecting an assortment

01:25.000 --> 01:29.000
And not the only product that the buyer needs to present

01:29.000 --> 01:34.000
The main thing is that the buyer came and found everything he needs in this trading point

01:34.000 --> 01:38.000
Therefore, he will not pay special attention to your product

01:38.000 --> 01:43.000
The next goal of the manufacturer is to create a competitive advantage of the product

01:43.000 --> 01:46.000
And what do we see from the seller?

01:46.000 --> 01:49.000
Of course, the creation of a competitive advantage of the store

01:49.000 --> 02:00.000
For example, there is a wider assortment, lower prices, convenient parking, or a complex with a store, cafe and entertainment center

02:00.000 --> 02:05.000
That is, the seller cares about the competitive advantage of the store as a whole

02:05.000 --> 02:08.000
It is a competitive advantage of our product

02:08.000 --> 02:11.000
Our goals do not converge here

02:11.000 --> 02:15.000
The next point is to create an attachment to the trademark, the manufacturer tells us

02:16.000 --> 02:19.000
What does the seller say?

02:19.000 --> 02:26.000
He just needs an optimal assortment of well-known brands that will attract certain buyers

02:26.000 --> 02:29.000
He does not care about the attachment to a particular brand

02:29.000 --> 02:33.000
He cares about the attachment to a package of well-known brands

02:33.000 --> 02:39.000
The next goal of the manufacturer is, of course, to avoid a situation when the product is absent in the trading point

02:39.000 --> 02:41.000
This is a very important point

02:41.000 --> 02:46.000
Because when your product is not there, the buyer just switches to another trading brand

02:46.000 --> 02:50.000
For the store, of course, it is also important that the full assortment is present

02:50.000 --> 02:53.000
But if there is no your product, they will put another one

02:53.000 --> 02:55.000
In general, there will be no problems

02:55.000 --> 02:59.000
Therefore, here you yourself must make sure that your product is present in the trading point

02:59.000 --> 03:04.000
And the next goal is to create an attachment to the positive image of the manufacturer

03:04.000 --> 03:08.000
The manufacturer says, it is important for me to be well perceived

03:08.000 --> 03:10.000
And what does the store say?

03:10.000 --> 03:13.000
The store says that it is important for him to be perceived in general

03:13.000 --> 03:16.000
The store is good, positive

03:16.000 --> 03:20.000
To have flexible conditions there, for example, in terms of working time

03:20.000 --> 03:23.000
For example, until the last buyer

03:23.000 --> 03:25.000
Or something like that

03:25.000 --> 03:28.000
That is, the store is important, of course, everything in general

03:28.000 --> 03:31.000
And our trading brand is important to us

03:31.000 --> 03:35.000
And these things need to be taken into account when we develop the standard of merchandising

03:35.000 --> 03:39.000
And we offer our products to the trading point

03:39.000 --> 03:42.000
Let's consider the main tasks of the merchandising company

03:42.000 --> 03:45.000
What should you pay attention to when you develop the standard

03:45.000 --> 03:48.000
Or when you determine the product schedule

03:48.000 --> 03:50.000
What you must take into account

03:50.000 --> 03:53.000
The first is the minimum set of assortment positions

03:53.000 --> 03:55.000
Or they also call it SKU

03:55.000 --> 03:58.000
Roughly speaking, one unit of the assortment

03:58.000 --> 04:03.000
That is, how many of you should have the layout of this assortment

04:03.000 --> 04:07.000
So that your layout looks high quality and good

04:08.000 --> 04:12.000
The next task is the place where your product is placed

04:12.000 --> 04:16.000
You must determine the category in which department your product is placed

04:16.000 --> 04:18.000
And in what place of the store

04:18.000 --> 04:21.000
The next task is the number of additional sales places

04:21.000 --> 04:24.000
This is very important, because additional sales places

04:24.000 --> 04:28.000
Give the opportunity for additional acquaintance with your product

04:28.000 --> 04:33.000
And, of course, there is your most popular product

04:33.000 --> 04:35.000
Which greatly increases the turnover

04:35.000 --> 04:40.000
You must determine in advance where it is possible to place additional places

04:40.000 --> 04:43.000
Next, you must determine the number of SKU

04:43.000 --> 04:46.000
How many assortment units of the product are set

04:46.000 --> 04:48.000
And the order of their placement

04:48.000 --> 04:52.000
For example, from light to dark, from the lowest price to the highest

04:52.000 --> 04:55.000
From the lowest fat to the highest, and so on

04:55.000 --> 04:58.000
That is, the order can be different depending on the product

04:58.000 --> 05:03.000
Depending on the colors, if the product is set from light to dark

05:03.000 --> 05:07.000
Or the combination of colors, or joint purchase

05:07.000 --> 05:10.000
That is, the rules can be different, there are a lot of them

05:10.000 --> 05:13.000
But nevertheless, you must immediately determine in the standard

05:13.000 --> 05:16.000
According to what rules you place this product

05:16.000 --> 05:19.000
The next point is the number of positions, or they also call it facing

05:19.000 --> 05:23.000
Look, the assortment is an assortment unit

05:23.000 --> 05:27.000
For example, you decided that you will put three office chairs

05:27.000 --> 05:31.000
But these three office chairs can be repeated, right?

05:31.000 --> 05:34.000
And there will be three SKU, because there are three different types

05:34.000 --> 05:38.000
And facing is how many chairs there will be

05:38.000 --> 05:42.000
Roughly speaking, if you put each SKU in two positions

05:42.000 --> 05:45.000
Then the facing will be equal to six

05:45.000 --> 05:48.000
The next thing to determine is the stock or the minimum load

05:48.000 --> 05:54.000
The stock must be such that it is constantly present on the shelf of the store

05:54.000 --> 05:58.000
And your product, even taking into account that it leaves this shelf

05:58.000 --> 06:02.000
That is, a certain stock must always be in the storehouse of the seller

06:02.000 --> 06:06.000
The next point is positioning the price relative to the competitors

06:06.000 --> 06:10.000
That is, you must immediately determine in what price category your product is located

06:10.000 --> 06:13.000
Because different price categories are distributed differently

06:13.000 --> 06:17.000
And actually, where this product will be located, next to which competitors

06:17.000 --> 06:21.000
And what is the recommended price of your product

06:21.000 --> 06:25.000
Because we know that each store gives its own rating, it is different

06:25.000 --> 06:28.000
Therefore, we must clearly determine what the rating will be

06:28.000 --> 06:32.000
The next point that is often determined by very famous manufacturers

06:32.000 --> 06:35.000
This is the share relative to the competitors of your product

06:35.000 --> 06:42.000
For example, you say that the share of our office chairs must be 50% relative to competitors

06:42.000 --> 06:44.000
That is, half of the categories should be occupied by us

06:44.000 --> 06:48.000
This is, of course, an ambitious goal, but nevertheless, such goals are set

06:48.000 --> 06:52.000
In order to ensure their recognition

06:52.000 --> 06:55.000
And two more points that we must talk about

06:55.000 --> 06:57.000
This is, of course, the placement of the price tags

06:57.000 --> 07:01.000
A clear and competent design is necessary and where they are placed

07:01.000 --> 07:04.000
In some stores there are price tag standards, this is great

07:04.000 --> 07:07.000
But in some stores they are simply not observed

07:07.000 --> 07:12.000
Therefore, where and how we place them must be necessarily agreed upon in the standard of merchandising

07:12.000 --> 07:15.000
And the last point is the schedule itself

07:15.000 --> 07:19.000
That is, we must draw out how, where and why our product is in what order

07:19.000 --> 07:24.000
So that the merchandising does not invent, compose and fantasize

07:24.000 --> 07:28.000
How to put it, how it will be better, how worse

07:28.000 --> 07:32.000
We must give him a clear instruction so that he does not touch it

07:32.000 --> 07:37.000
Only this will ensure you increased sales and efficiency of this tool

07:37.000 --> 07:43.000
All the basic rules of merchandising will be described in your lecture material

07:43.000 --> 07:47.000
Which will help you to correctly form a schedule and a standard of merchandising

07:47.000 --> 07:50.000
These rules are divided into three groups

07:50.000 --> 07:53.000
This is the location, presentation and stock

07:53.000 --> 07:59.000
You can decode all of them there, look at the rules of the layout

07:59.000 --> 08:05.000
And, in fact, create your own merchandising standard

08:05.000 --> 08:09.000
And about the location itself, I would like to say a few more words

08:09.000 --> 08:13.000
And show you the hot and cold zones in the store

08:14.000 --> 08:17.000
To understand where you can put your product and where not

08:17.000 --> 08:21.000
Here is an image on the slide

08:21.000 --> 08:26.000
And there you see that all 100% that enter the store

08:26.000 --> 08:30.000
Only 90% of them are in the first square

08:30.000 --> 08:33.000
The other 10% take what is needed and go to the checkout

08:33.000 --> 08:35.000
Or return, leaving the store

08:35.000 --> 08:39.000
Then, along the way, only 70% pass

08:40.000 --> 08:43.000
The other 20% have already taken the product and gone to the checkout

08:43.000 --> 08:46.000
Only 50% pass further

